goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if the frequency of disasters is increasing or decreasing over time.

goals.visualization: bar chart of total deaths by disaster type
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify the most deadly types of disasters and prioritize disaster preparedness efforts accordingly.

goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the range and frequency of deaths caused by disasters.

goals.visualization: stacked area chart of number of disasters by type over the years
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify if certain types of disasters are becoming more or less frequent over time.

goals.question: What is the correlation between the number of deaths and the year of the disaster?

goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is a trend in the number of deaths caused by disasters over time.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Year'], format='%Y', errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['Year'])]
    
    yearly_disasters = data.groupby('Year').size().reset_index(name='Number of Disasters')
    
    plt.plot(yearly_disasters['Year'], yearly_disasters['Number of Disasters'])
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Disasters')
    plt.title('What is the overall trend of disasters over the years?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend(['Number of Disasters'])
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Group data by disaster type and sum the deaths
    total_deaths_by_disaster = data.groupby('Entity')['Deaths'].sum().reset_index()

    # Sort the data by total deaths in descending order
    total_deaths_by_disaster = total_deaths_by_disaster.sort_values('Deaths', ascending=False)

    # Create a bar chart
    plt.bar(total_deaths_by_disaster['Entity'], total_deaths_by_disaster['Deaths'])

    # Set the chart title
    plt.title('Which type of disaster has caused the most deaths?', wrap=True)

    # Set the x-axis label
    plt.xlabel('Disaster Type')

    # Set the y-axis label
    plt.ylabel('Total Deaths')

    # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)

    # Add a legend
    plt.legend(['Total Deaths'])

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.hist(data['Deaths'], bins=50, color='blue', alpha=0.7)
    plt.axvline(data['Deaths'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2, label=f"Median: {data['Deaths'].median():.2f}")
    plt.xlabel('Deaths')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of deaths caused by disasters?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Year'], format='%Y', errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['Year'])]
    
    disaster_counts = data.groupby(['Year', 'Entity']).size().unstack().fillna(0)
    disaster_counts.plot(kind='area', stacked=True)
    
    plt.title("How has the frequency of each type of disaster changed over time?", wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel("Year")
    plt.ylabel("Number of Disasters")
    plt.legend(title="Disaster Type", loc="upper left")
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    scatter = ax.scatter(data['Year'], data['Deaths'], c=data['Entity'].cat.codes, cmap='viridis', alpha=0.5)
    ax.set_xlabel('Year')
    ax.set_ylabel('Deaths')
    ax.set_title('What is the correlation between the number of deaths and the year of the disaster?', wrap=True)
    legend1 = ax.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(), title="Disaster Types")
    ax.add_artist(legend1)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
